<subSubSection box="[151,419,151,178]" pageId="7" pageNumber="348" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,419,151,178]" box="[151,419,151,178]" pageId="7" pageNumber="348">
<heading bold="true" box="[151,419,151,178]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="7" pageNumber="348" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,419,151,178]" pageId="7" pageNumber="348">
The 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Puplesis &amp; Robinson" authorityYear="1999" box="[207,337,151,178]" class="Insecta" family="Opostegidae" genus="Pseudopostega" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="348" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="indonesica">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[207,337,151,178]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="348">indonesica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="348" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,223,754]" pageId="7" pageNumber="348">
Externally, species are characterized by a wide, dark brown or ochre fascia of the forewing; snow white frontal tuft. In the male genitalia, the uncus is comprised of two large, distally rounded lateral lobes; the gnathos is a small plate with large lateral arms and a large, distally rounded caudal process; the valva has a large, distinctive pedicel and triangular cucullar lobes; and the vinculum is bilobed anteriorly, with a distinctive, strongly thickened, rod-like juxta (
<figureCitation box="[160,224,367,393]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1904,1928]" captionTargetBox="[177,1411,192,1870]" captionTargetId="figure-18@4.[169,1417,181,1880]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 1. Pictorial diagnostic tool for identification of Oriental Pseudopostega species groups (Note: the morphological structures are drawn in different scales). * – except for P. similantis with an indistinctive dorsal spot; ** – formerly the nigrimaculella group; *** – Mediterranean P. matrona sp. nov., described below" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4554948" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4554948/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="348">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
). In the female genitalia, the apophyses are unique in comparison with other 
<taxonomicName box="[1078,1248,367,393]" class="Insecta" family="Opostegidae" genus="Pseudopostega" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="348" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1078,1248,367,393]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="348">Pseudopostega</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
because they are very long; the anal papillae with two deeply divided lobes (
<figureCitation box="[816,881,403,429]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1904,1928]" captionTargetBox="[177,1411,192,1870]" captionTargetId="figure-18@4.[169,1417,181,1880]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 1. Pictorial diagnostic tool for identification of Oriental Pseudopostega species groups (Note: the morphological structures are drawn in different scales). * – except for P. similantis with an indistinctive dorsal spot; ** – formerly the nigrimaculella group; *** – Mediterranean P. matrona sp. nov., described below" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4554948" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4554948/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="348">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
); and the signum is absent.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="348" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,223,754]" pageId="7" pageNumber="348">
From other groups of Oriental 
<taxonomicName box="[552,722,439,465]" class="Insecta" family="Opostegidae" genus="Pseudopostega" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="348" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[552,722,439,465]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="348">Pseudopostega</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Puplesis &amp; Robinson" authorityYear="1999" box="[780,901,439,465]" class="Insecta" family="Opostegidae" genus="Pseudopostega" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="348" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="indonesica">
<emphasis box="[780,901,439,465]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="348">indonesica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group is easily distinguished by the deeply bilobed vinculum, distinctive pedicel of the valva in the male genitalia, and the very long apophyses and deeply divided lobes of the anal papillae in the female genitalia.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="348" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,223,754]" pageId="7" pageNumber="348">
Distribution. Currently the group is comprised of two species distributed in 
<collectingCountry box="[1075,1187,547,573]" name="Indonesia" pageId="7" pageNumber="348">Indonesia</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1200,1260,547,573]" name="India" pageId="7" pageNumber="348">India</collectingCountry>
, and 
<collectingCountry box="[1324,1436,547,573]" name="Sri Lanka" pageId="7" pageNumber="348">Sri Lanka</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Davis, D. R." box="[159,293,583,609]" pageId="7" pageNumber="348" pagination="1 - 97" refId="ref9399" refString="Davis, D. R. (1989) Generic revision of the Opostegidae, with a synoptic catalog of the world's species (Lepidoptera: Nepticuloidea). Smithsonian Contributions to Zoology, 478, i-iii + 1 - 97. https: // doi. org / 10.5479 / si. 00810282.478" type="journal article" year="1989">Davis 1989</bibRefCitation>
), and possibly with wider distribution (D. R. Davis 
<emphasis box="[872,1001,584,609]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="348">pers. comm</emphasis>
.) (
<figureCitation box="[1033,1098,583,609]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1904,1928]" captionTargetBox="[177,1411,192,1870]" captionTargetId="figure-18@4.[169,1417,181,1880]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 1. Pictorial diagnostic tool for identification of Oriental Pseudopostega species groups (Note: the morphological structures are drawn in different scales). * – except for P. similantis with an indistinctive dorsal spot; ** – formerly the nigrimaculella group; *** – Mediterranean P. matrona sp. nov., described below" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4554948" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4554948/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="348">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="348" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,223,754]" pageId="7" pageNumber="348">
Remarks. Previously, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Meyrick" baseAuthorityYear="1907" box="[447,565,620,645]" class="Insecta" family="Opostegidae" genus="Pseudopostega" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="348" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="euryntis">
<emphasis box="[447,565,620,645]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="348">P. euryntis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was left unplaced in a species group (
<bibRefCitation author="Puplesis, R. &amp; Robinson, G. S." box="[999,1307,619,645]" pageId="7" pageNumber="348" pagination="1 - 92" refId="ref11121" refString="Puplesis, R. &amp; Robinson, G. S. (1999) Revision of the Oriental Opostegidae (Lepidoptera) with general comments on phylogeny within the family. Bulletin of the Natural History Museum, London, Entomology, 68 (1), 1 - 92." type="journal article" year="1999">Puplesis &amp; Robinson 1999</bibRefCitation>
). However, upon the study of the female 
<typeStatus box="[470,568,655,681]" pageId="7" pageNumber="348">holotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Meyrick" baseAuthorityYear="1907" box="[603,719,656,681]" class="Insecta" family="Opostegidae" genus="Pseudopostega" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="348" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="euryntis">
<emphasis box="[603,719,656,681]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="348">P. euryntis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
we found it possesses all the diagnostic characters of the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Puplesis &amp; Robinson" authorityYear="1999" class="Insecta" family="Opostegidae" genus="Pseudopostega" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="348" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="indonesica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="348">indonesica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group: very long apophyses and deeply divided lobes of anal papillae. Therefore, we newly attribute 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Meyrick" baseAuthorityYear="1907" box="[1319,1436,692,717]" class="Insecta" family="Opostegidae" genus="Pseudopostega" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="348" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="euryntis">
<emphasis box="[1319,1436,692,717]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="348">P. euryntis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Puplesis &amp; Robinson" authorityYear="1999" box="[221,342,727,753]" class="Insecta" family="Opostegidae" genus="Pseudopostega" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="348" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="indonesica">
<emphasis box="[221,342,727,753]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="348">indonesica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group (see Checklist).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
